.NET Framework 3.5.name: VRTK_PolicyList
.NET Framework 3.5.summary: The Policy List allows to create a list of either tag names, script names or layer names that can be checked against to see if another operation is permitted.
.NET Framework 3.5.remarks:
A number of other scripts can use a Policy List to determine if an operation is permitted based on whether a game object has a tag applied, a script component on it or whether it's on a given layer.

 For example, the Teleporter scripts can ignore game object targets as a teleport location if the game object contains a tag that is in the identifiers list and the policy is set to ignore. 
 
 Or the teleporter can only allow teleport to targets that contain a tag that is in the identifiers list and the policy is set to include. 
 
 Add the Policy List script to a game object (preferably the same component utilising the list) and then configure the list accordingly. 
 
 Then in the component that has a Policy List paramter (e.g. BasicTeleporter has `Target List Policy`) simply select the list that has been created and defined.

methods.name: Check(GameObject obj, VRTK_PolicyList list)
methods.summary: The Check method is used to check if a game object should be ignored based on a given string or policy list.
methods.returns: Returns true of the given game object matches the policy list or given string logic.

params.value: The policy list to use for checking.

methods.syntax: public static bool Check(GameObject obj, VRTK_PolicyList list)
methods.linkedSyntax: public static bool Check(GameObject obj, [VRTK_PolicyList](#/type/VRTK.VRTK_PolicyList/index) list)

methods.name: Find(GameObject obj)
methods.summary: The Find method performs the set operation to determine if the given game object contains one of the identifiers on the set check type.
methods.remarks: For instance, if the Operation is Ignore and the Check Type is Tag then the Find method will attempt to see if the given game object has a tag that matches one of the identifiers.
methods.returns: If the operation is Ignore and the game object is matched by an identifier from the list then it returns true. If the operation is Include and the game object is not matched by an identifier from the list then it returns true.

params.value: The game object to check if it has a tag or script that is listed in the identifiers list.
